on’s exhibition Power & Light—and includes his original, detailed captions as well as an essay by biographer Mary Jane Appel and historian Douglas Brinkley. They place his work in context and illuminate how Lee helped win improved conditions for his subjects through vivid images that captured an array of miners and their communities at work and at play, at church and in school, in moments of joy and struggle, ultimately revealing to their fellow Americans the humanity and resilience of these underrecognized workers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCoal minersxHealth and hygienezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th centuryvPictorial works. 0aCoal minerszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th centuryvPictorial works. 0aCoal minerszUnited StatesxSocial life and customsy20th centuryvPictorial works. 0aLabor disputeszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th centuryvPictorial works. 0aMining campszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th centuryvPictorial works. 7aPhotography / General.2bisacsh  aNational Archives, social documentary photography, United Mine Workers Association UMWA, Medical Survey of the Bituminous-Coal Industry, Coal Country U.S.A., coal mines 1940s, environmental degradation, Appalachia, Truman administration, Executive Order 9728.1 aBrinkley, Douglas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079783140uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32956640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477329658423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477329658/original  a978-3-11-079783-1  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles